e highlights global interconnectedness seen through the prism of the Middle East, both “global-in” and “global-out.” It delves into the region’s scientific, artistic, economic, political, religious, and intellectual formations and traces how they have taken shape through a dynamic set of encounters and exchanges. Written in short and accessible essays by prominent experts on the region, Global Middle East covers topics including God, Rumi, food, film, fashion, music, sports, science, and the flow of people, goods, and ideas. The text explores social and political movements from human rights, Salafism, and cosmopolitanism to radicalism and revolutions. Using the insights of global studies, students will glean new perspectives about the region.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aGlobalizationzMiddle East. 0aRegionalismzMiddle East. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Middle Eastern Studies.2bisacsh1 aAli, Amro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Lori, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBayat, Asef, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBayat, Asef, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDabashi, Hamid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFahmy, Khaled, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeldman, Ilana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrishkopf, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHazbun, Waleed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerrera, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKanna, Ahmed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaram, John Tofik, econtrib